{"title_page": "Tony Taccone", "text_new": "{{short description|American theatre director}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Tony Taccone\n| image              = \n| imagesize          = \n| caption            = \n| birth_name         = \n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1951|07|04}}\n| birth_place        = [[Queens, New York]], [[United States|USA]]\n| othername          = \n| occupation         = [[Theatre director]]\n| spouse             = Suellen Ehnebuske (divorced); Morgan Forsey (current spouse/partner)\n| yearsactive        = 1981 to present\n}}\n\n'''Tony Taccone''' (born July 4, 1951) is an American [[theater director]], and the former Artistic Director of [[Berkeley Repertory Theatre]] in [[Berkeley, California]]. \n\n==Early life==\nTony Taccone was born on July 4, 1951 in [[Queens, New York]], to an Italian-American father and a Puerto Rican mother.<ref name=Hurwitt>Hurwitt, Robert (July 5, 2006), [http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/c/a/2006/07/05/DDGERJNJ4K1.DTL \"Tony Taccone: Riding high on his recent successes, theater veteran has big plans for Berkeley Rep\"]. ''Chronicle Theater Critic''. (accessed 2009-05-18)</ref>  They encouraged their children to go into the arts; their daughter became a photographer, and both sons found careers in theater.<ref name=Hurwitt/>\n\nTaccone, attended Boston College as an English major. He frequently participated in poetry readings, which led to performance art.<ref name=Hurwitt/> After marrying, he accompanied his wife to the University of Colorado and became involved in the drama department.  His acting troupe asked him to fill in for their sick director and stage the next play. Taccone called the gig the \"closest thing I ever had to an epiphany,\" and permanently went behind the curtain.<ref name=Hurwitt/>  After graduating, Taccone enrolled in UC Berkeley in the doctoral directing program, where he became close friends with fellow student [[Richard E.T. White]].<ref name=Hurwitt/>\n\n==Career==\n{{quote box|width=250px|align=left|quote=The one thing you cannot do in comedy is to go for the laugh.<ref name=souza>D'SOUZA, KAREN (May/June 2009), \"Looking for Laughs with Amy Freed\". ''American Theatre''. '''26''' (5):50-53</ref>|source=''American Theater'' magazine}}When White became artistic director of the Eureka Theatre, a converted warehouse in San Francisco's Mission District,<ref name=McLaughlin>McLaughlin, Ellen (September 2006), \"In Cahoots with Tony Taccone\". ''American Theatre''. '''23''' (7):26-58</ref> he invited Taccone along. In 1981, White left and Taccone replaced him as the artistic director.<ref name=McLaughlin/>  It was there that Taccone began his partnership with [[Tony Kushner]], who he commissioned to write what Kushner thought would be a short chamber piece called ''[[Angels in America]]''.<ref name=McLaughlin/> Over Taccone's tenure there, the Eureka's annual budget grew from $60,000 to $780,000 as their subscriber number grew to 2,400 and the repertory moved to a new building because their theater was destroyed by an arsonist.<ref name=GOODWIN>Goodwin, Joy (March 2, 2008), \"Left Coast Ideas, Floating East\". ''New York Times''.</ref> Despite the growth, they required $1.3 million in order to stay afloat, and talks began that the repertory could not sustain its artists with growing families.<ref name=Hurwitt/><ref name=McLaughlin/>  Taccone was extremely reluctant to leave, but announced his resignation in 1988.<ref name=McLaughlin/>\n\nThat year, Taccone became the associate artistic director of [[Berkeley Rep]] under Sharon Ott, again replacing White.<ref name=Hurwitt/><ref name=McLaughlin/>  Right around that time, ''[[Angels in America]]'', which ended up becoming a two-part, seven-hour epic, was becoming a national sensation critically and otherwise, and a boon to the Eureka. Four years later (in 1992), he and Oskar Eustis co-directed the world premiere of the complete work at the [[Mark Taper Forum]].<ref name=Hurwitt/>  In 1997, Berkeley Rep won a Tony for Best Regional Theater.<ref name=Hurwitt/>  That year, Ott left to become artistic director of [[Seattle Repertory]],<ref name=Hurwitt/> and Taccone became full artistic director,<ref>(May/June 2009), \"KUSHNER'S BAC, AND THE GUTHRIE'S GOT HIM\". ''American Theatre''. '''26''' (5):12</ref> where he has staged more than 35 shows,<ref name=taccone>Taccone, Tony (Winter/Spring 2007), \"Culture Clash's Zorro in Hell\". ''TheatreForum''. (30):74</ref> including the world premieres of [[Continental Divide]] and [[Culture Clash in AmeriCCa]].  He has collaborated with Kushner on six projects.<ref name=taccone/> Their latest piece featured designs by beloved children\u2019s author, ''[[Maurice Sendak]]: [[Brundibar]]'' debuted at Berkeley Rep and then traveled to [[Yale Rep]] and the [[New Victory Theater]] in New York City.<ref name=taccone/> Taccone made his Broadway debut with [[Sarah Jones (stage actress)|Sarah Jones]]\u2019s ''[[Bridge and Tunnel (play)|Bridge & Tunnel]]''. He also staged the show\u2019s record-breaking off-Broadway run at Culture Project, workshopped it for Broadway at Berkeley Rep and directed Jones\u2019 previous hit, ''[[Surface Transit]]''. Taccone frequently works at Ashland\u2019s [[Oregon Shakespeare Festival]], where he has directed [[Coriolanus]], [[Othello]], [[Pentecost]], the American premiere of [[Seamus Heaney]]\u2019s [[The Cure at Troy]], and his production of [[David Edgar (playwright)|David Edgar]]\u2019s [[Continental Divide]], which also played at the [[Berkeley Rep]] and in England at [[Birmingham Rep]] and London\u2019s [[Barbican Centre]]. His other regional credits include noted theatres such as [[Actors Theatre of Louisville]], [[Arizona Rep]], [[La Jolla Playhouse]],<ref name=taccone/> [[San Jose Rep]], [[Seattle Rep]] and [[San Francisco\u2019s Eureka Theatre]], where he served six years as artistic director before coming to Berkeley Rep. Taccone has served on the faculty of [[U.C. Berkeley]], sat on the board of [[Theatre Communications Group]] and acted as a regional representative for the [[Stage Directors and Choreographers Society]].<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">Berkeley Repertory Theatre, berkeleyrep.org</ref>\n\nPlaybill recently asserted that \"Tony Taccone may very well be the most prominent artistic director in America right now.\" <ref name=SIMONSON>[[Simonson, Robert]] (October 30, 2009), [http://www.playbill.com/celebritybuzz/article/134217-PLAYBILLCOMS-BRIEF-ENCOUNTER-With-Tony-Taccone- \"Playbill.com's Brief Encounter with Tony Taccone\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110210105459/http://www.playbill.com/celebritybuzz/article/134217-PLAYBILLCOMS-BRIEF-ENCOUNTER-With-Tony-Taccone- |date=2011-02-10 }}.</ref> During his tenure, Berkeley Rep has emerged as the source of many important Broadway shows, including Green Day's ''American Idiot,'' Sarah Ruhl's ''In the Next Room, or the vibrator play,'' Carrie Fisher's ''Wishful Drinking,'' Sarah Jones' ''Bridge & Tunnel,'' and ''Passing Strange.'' <ref name=Hurwitt2>HURWITT, ROBERT (October 16, 2009), \"Berkeley Rep a big success on Broadway\". ''San Francisco Chronicle''.</ref><ref name=WEBER>WEBER, BRUCE (October 25, 2009), \"Two Tonys and Their 'Tiny' Five-Act Play\". ''New York Times''.</ref> Two of Taccone\u2019s recent shows also transferred to London: ''Continental Divide'' played the Barbican in 2004, and ''Tiny Kushner'' played the Tricycle Theatre in 2010.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/> \n\nTaccone's professional career has included fostering [[clowning]], a fascination he developed when he went to take his small family to see the [[Pickle Family Circus]] in the 1980s.  He favors clown artistry that is a reaction to tragedy.<ref name=McLaughlin/>\n\nTaccone has been called a \"theatrical midwife\" because he often encourages and fosters new talent.<ref name=McLaughlin/>  Examples include his work with Sarah Jones on ''Surface Transit'' and the aforementioned Tony Kushner.<ref name=McLaughlin/>\n\nIn 2009, Taccone participated in ''A Night With the Stars'', a play performed by persons who were previously homeless. The play was done as a fundraiser for [[Community Housing Partnership]] in San Francisco.<ref>Rubien, David (April 19, 2009), [http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/c/a/2009/04/19/PK9816MSAE.DTL&hw=tony+taccone&sn=003&sc=492 \"This week: Arts and entertainment picks\"]. SFGate.com (accessed 2009-05-19)</ref>\n\nTaccone made his playwriting debut in May 2011 with his solo show for Rita Moreno<ref>Jones, Kenneth (March 3, 2010) [http://www.playbill.com/news/article/137473-Lemony-Snicket-Rita-Moreno-The-Great-Game-Will-Be-Part-of-Berkeley-Rep-in-2010-11-Season-Announced \"Lemony Snicket, Rita Moreno, The Great Game Will Be Part of Berkeley Rep in 2010-11; Season Announced\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100306072221/http://www.playbill.com/news/article/137473-Lemony-Snicket-Rita-Moreno-The-Great-Game-Will-Be-Part-of-Berkeley-Rep-in-2010-11-Season-Announced |date=2010-03-06 }}</ref> and followed this up with his show ''Ghost Light'' at the Oregon Shakespeare Festival in 2011, which he co-created with Jonathan Moscone.<ref>Hughley, Marty (March 12, 2010), [http://www.oregonlive.com/performance/index.ssf/2010/03/oregon_shakespeare_festival_an_3.html \"Ashland's Oregon Shakespeare Festival announces plays for 2011 season\"].</ref>\n\nTaccone directed the original musical ''Kiss My Aztec'', which he co-wrote with [[John Leguizamo]] (score by [[Benjamin Velez]] and David Kamp). It was developed at the [[Public Theater]] in 2018 and premiered at [[Berkeley Repertory Theater]] and [[La Jolla Playhouse]] in 2019, where it received critical acclaim<ref>{{cite web|url=https://datebook.sfchronicle.com/theater/review-berkeley-reps-kiss-my-aztec-brings-past-to-present-and-future|title=Review: Berkeley Rep\u2019s \u2018Kiss My Aztec!\u2019 brings past to present and future|date=June 7, 2019|work=[[Datebook]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sfexaminer.com/entertainment/kiss-my-aztec-turns-the-historical-hysterical/|title=\u2018Kiss My Aztec\u2019 turns the historical hysterical|date=June 7, 2019|work=[[San Francisco Examiner]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.broadwayworld.com/amp/c.php?url=BWW-Review-KISS-MY-AZTEC-at-Berkeley-Repertory-Theatre-is-a-Hilarious-Socially-Hip-Historical-Romp-Through-the-Aztec-Empire-20190618|title=BWW Review: KISS MY AZTEC! at Berkeley Repertory Theatre is  a Hilarious, Socially Hip Historical Romp Through the Aztec Empire|date=June 18, 2019|work=[[Broadway World]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/entertainment/theater/story/2019-09-09/john-leguizamos-kiss-my-aztec-a-messy-but-entertaining-musical-ode-to-some-twisted-history|title=Review: John Leguizamo\u2019s \u2018Kiss My Aztec!\u2019 a splashy and entertaining musical ode that puts a twist on history|date=September 9, 2019|work=[[The San Diego Union-Tribune]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofsandiego.com/arts/2019/09/10/la-jolla-playhouses-kiss-my-aztec-takes-a-wildly-satirical-look-at-colonial-history/|title=La Jolla Playhouse\u2019s \u2018Kiss My Aztec!\u2019 Takes a Wildly Satirical Look at Colonial History|date=September 10, 2019|work=[[Times of San Diego]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.broadwayworld.com/article/Review-Roundup-What-Did-Critics-Think-of-KISS-MY-AZTEC-at-La-Jolla-Playhouse-20190912|title=Review Roundup: What Did Critics Think of KISS MY AZTEC! at La Jolla Playhouse?|date=September 12, 2019|work=[[Broadway World]]}}</ref>.\n\nIn 2019, Taccone ended his 33 year tenure as Artistic Director of [[Berkeley Repertory Theatre]], handing the position over to Johanna Pfaelzer. \n\n==Personal life==\n{{quote box|width=280px|quote=You can have a healthy, happy life and still be indelibly connected to the deeper sorrow of the world. You don't need to create personal trauma to experience darkness. In fact, in some rarefied theological schools of thought, one could argue the opposite.<ref name=McLaughlin/>|source=''American Theater'' magazine, 2006}}\n\nTaccone is married to Morgan Forsey.<ref name=\"Bigelow\">{{cite news |last1=Bigelow |first1=Catherine |title=Cal Shakes gala raises curtain on education |url=https://www.pressreader.com/ |accessdate=3 February 2019 |work=San Francisco Chronicle |date=March 20, 2013}}</ref> Taccone's children include [[Jorma Taccone]],<ref>Jones, Chad (August 30, 2007), [http://blogs.mercurynews.com/aei/2007/08/30/brt40-a-chat-with-tony-taccone/ \"BRT@40: A chat with Tony Taccone\"]{{Dead link|date=July 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=no }}. MercuryNews.com (accessed 2009-05-18)</ref> (a member of the sketch-comedy troupe [[the Lonely Island]] and a former-writer for ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'') and [[Asa Taccone]], a musician and sometimes collaborator with his brother.<ref name=Hurwitt/>  Asa is a founding member of the band [[Electric Guest]] and has composed music for his father's productions, such as for ''Bridge & Tunnel'' and Taking Over.<ref>SCHIFFMAN, JEAN (January 22, 2006), [http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117936534.html?categoryId=1228&cs=1 \"Helmer Taccone expands his 'Tunnel' vision\"]. Variety.com (accessed 2009-05-19)</ref><ref>BWW News Desk (January 21, 2009), [http://broadwayworld.com/people/news/Danny_Hoch/ \"Danny Hoch's TAKING OVER Previews Tonight 1/21\"]. BroadwayWorld.com (accessed 2009-05-19)</ref>\n\n==Theater credits==\n*''Honour'', Berkeley Repertory Theatre - director\n*''Continental Divide'', Berkeley Repertory Theatre - director\n*''Surface Transit'', Berkeley Repertory Theatre - director\n*''Cloud Nine'', Berkeley Repertory Theatre - director\n*''Homebody/Kabul'', Berkeley Repertory Theatre - director\n*''Culture Clash in AmeriCCa'', Berkeley Repertory Theatre - director\n*''The Oresteia'', Berkeley Repertory Theatre - director\n*''Ravenshead'', Berkeley Repertory Theatre - director\n*''Pentecost, Slavs!'', Berkeley Repertory Theatre - director\n*''The Caucasian Chalk Circle'', Berkeley Repertory Theatre - director\n*''Endgame/Act Without Words'', Berkeley Repertory Theatre - director\n*''Volpone'', Berkeley Repertory Theatre - director\n*''The Convict\u2019s Return'', Berkeley Repertory Theatre - director\n*''Major Barbara'', Berkeley Repertory Theatre - director\n*''Serious Money'', Berkeley Repertory Theatre - director\n*''Waiting for Godot'' - director\n*''[[Othello]]'', Oregon Shakespeare Festival - director\n*Pentecost, Oregon Shakespeare Festival - director\n*''[[Coriolanus]]'', Oregon Shakespeare Festival - director\n*''[[The Cure at Troy]]'', Oregon Shakespeare Festival - director\n*''The Birthday Party and Execution of Justice'', Berkeley Repertory Theatre\n* ''[[Waiting for Godot]]'' (1989) - director\n* ''[[Angels in America]], Parts One and Two'', Mark Taper Forum (1992) - director\n* ''Brundibar'' (2006), New Victory Theater - director\n* ''Zorro in Hell'' (2006) - director\n* ''Wishful Drinking'' (2008), Berkeley Repertory Theatre - director<ref>Hurwitt, Robert (April 30, 2009), [http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/c/a/2009/04/30/DDTP17ATQ4.DTL&hw=tony+taccone&sn=001&sc=1000 \"Fisher's 'Wishful Drinking' is Broadway-bound\"]. (SFGate.com. (accessed 2009-05-19)</ref>\n* ''Taking Over'', (2009) - director\n*Kiss My Aztec, (2019), Berkeley Repertory Theatre - director\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/blogs/chroncast/detail?blogid=5&entry_id=6727 Tony Taccone, Berkeley Rep Theatre's artistic director], podcast <small>([http://cdn.sfgate.com/blogs/sounds/sfgate/chroncast/2006/07/03/BackStory-Taccone-20060705.mp3 audio link])</small>\n\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Taccone, Tony}}\n[[Category:1951 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American theatre directors]]\n[[Category:American people of Italian descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Puerto Rican descent]]\n[[Category:Boston College alumni]]\n[[Category:Theatre in the San Francisco Bay Area]]\n[[Category:People from the San Francisco Bay Area]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American theatre director}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Tony Taccone\n| image              = \n| imagesize          = \n| caption            = \n| birth_name         = \n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1951|07|04}}\n| birth_place        = [[Queens, New York]], [[United States|USA]]\n| othername          = \n| occupation         = [[Theatre director]]\n| spouse             = Suellen Ehnebuske (divorced); Morgan Forsey (current spouse/partner)\n| yearsactive        = 1981 to present\n}}\n\n'''Tony Taccone''' (born July 4, 1951) is an American [[theater director]], and the former Artistic Director of [[Berkeley Repertory Theatre]] in [[Berkeley, California]]. \n\n==Early life==\nTony Taccone was born on July 4, 1951 in [[Queens, New York]], to an Italian-American father and a Puerto Rican mother.<ref name=Hurwitt>Hurwitt, Robert (July 5, 2006), [http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/c/a/2006/07/05/DDGERJNJ4K1.DTL \"Tony Taccone: Riding high on his recent successes, theater veteran has big plans for Berkeley Rep\"]. ''Chronicle Theater Critic''. (accessed 2009-05-18)</ref>  They encouraged their children to go into the arts; their daughter became a photographer, and both sons found careers in theater.<ref name=Hurwitt/>\n\nTaccone, attended Boston College as an English major. He frequently participated in poetry readings, which led to performance art.<ref name=Hurwitt/> After marrying, he accompanied his wife to the University of Colorado and became involved in the drama department.  His acting troupe asked him to fill in for their sick director and stage the next play. Taccone called the gig the \"closest thing I ever had to an epiphany,\" and permanently went behind the curtain.<ref name=Hurwitt/>  After graduating, Taccone enrolled in UC Berkeley in the doctoral directing program, where he became close friends with fellow student [[Richard E.T. White]].<ref name=Hurwitt/>\n\n==Career==\n{{quote box|width=250px|align=left|quote=The one thing you cannot do in comedy is to go for the laugh.<ref name=souza>D'SOUZA, KAREN (May/June 2009), \"Looking for Laughs with Amy Freed\". ''American Theatre''. '''26''' (5):50-53</ref>|source=''American Theater'' magazine}}When White became artistic director of the Eureka Theatre, a converted warehouse in San Francisco's Mission District,<ref name=McLaughlin>McLaughlin, Ellen (September 2006), \"In Cahoots with Tony Taccone\". ''American Theatre''. '''23''' (7):26-58</ref> he invited Taccone along. In 1981, White left and Taccone replaced him as the artistic director.<ref name=McLaughlin/>  It was there that Taccone began his partnership with [[Tony Kushner]], who he commissioned to write what Kushner thought would be a short chamber piece called ''[[Angels in America]]''.<ref name=McLaughlin/> Over Taccone's tenure there, the Eureka's annual budget grew from $60,000 to $780,000 as their subscriber number grew to 2,400 and the repertory moved to a new building because their theater was destroyed by an arsonist.<ref name=GOODWIN>Goodwin, Joy (March 2, 2008), \"Left Coast Ideas, Floating East\". ''New York Times''.</ref> Despite the growth, they required $1.3 million in order to stay afloat, and talks began that the repertory could not sustain its artists with growing families.<ref name=Hurwitt/><ref name=McLaughlin/>  Taccone was extremely reluctant to leave, but announced his resignation in 1988.<ref name=McLaughlin/>\n\nThat year, Taccone became the associate artistic director of [[Berkeley Rep]] under Sharon Ott, again replacing White.<ref name=Hurwitt/><ref name=McLaughlin/>  Right around that time, ''[[Angels in America]]'', which ended up becoming a two-part, seven-hour epic, was becoming a national sensation critically and otherwise, and a boon to the Eureka. Four years later (in 1992), he and Oskar Eustis co-directed the world premiere of the complete work at the [[Mark Taper Forum]].<ref name=Hurwitt/>  In 1997, Berkeley Rep won a Tony for Best Regional Theater.<ref name=Hurwitt/>  That year, Ott left to become artistic director of [[Seattle Repertory]],<ref name=Hurwitt/> and Taccone became full artistic director,<ref>(May/June 2009), \"KUSHNER'S BAC, AND THE GUTHRIE'S GOT HIM\". ''American Theatre''. '''26''' (5):12</ref> where he has staged more than 35 shows,<ref name=taccone>Taccone, Tony (Winter/Spring 2007), \"Culture Clash's Zorro in Hell\". ''TheatreForum''. (30):74</ref> including the world premieres of [[Continental Divide]] and [[Culture Clash in AmeriCCa]].  He has collaborated with Kushner on six projects.<ref name=taccone/> Their latest piece featured designs by beloved children\u2019s author, ''[[Maurice Sendak]]: [[Brundibar]]'' debuted at Berkeley Rep and then traveled to [[Yale Rep]] and the [[New Victory Theater]] in New York City.<ref name=taccone/> Taccone made his Broadway debut with [[Sarah Jones (stage actress)|Sarah Jones]]\u2019s ''[[Bridge and Tunnel (play)|Bridge & Tunnel]]''. He also staged the show\u2019s record-breaking off-Broadway run at Culture Project, workshopped it for Broadway at Berkeley Rep and directed Jones\u2019 previous hit, ''[[Surface Transit]]''. Taccone frequently works at Ashland\u2019s [[Oregon Shakespeare Festival]], where he has directed [[Coriolanus]], [[Othello]], [[Pentecost]], the American premiere of [[Seamus Heaney]]\u2019s [[The Cure at Troy]], and his production of [[David Edgar (playwright)|David Edgar]]\u2019s [[Continental Divide]], which also played at the [[Berkeley Rep]] and in England at [[Birmingham Rep]] and London\u2019s [[Barbican Centre]]. His other regional credits include noted theatres such as [[Actors Theatre of Louisville]], [[Arizona Rep]], [[La Jolla Playhouse]],<ref name=taccone/> [[San Jose Rep]], [[Seattle Rep]] and [[San Francisco\u2019s Eureka Theatre]], where he served six years as artistic director before coming to Berkeley Rep. Taccone has served on the faculty of [[U.C. Berkeley]], sat on the board of [[Theatre Communications Group]] and acted as a regional representative for the [[Stage Directors and Choreographers Society]].<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">Berkeley Repertory Theatre, berkeleyrep.org</ref>\n\nPlaybill recently asserted that \"Tony Taccone may very well be the most prominent artistic director in America right now.\" <ref name=SIMONSON>[[Simonson, Robert]] (October 30, 2009), [http://www.playbill.com/celebritybuzz/article/134217-PLAYBILLCOMS-BRIEF-ENCOUNTER-With-Tony-Taccone- \"Playbill.com's Brief Encounter with Tony Taccone\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110210105459/http://www.playbill.com/celebritybuzz/article/134217-PLAYBILLCOMS-BRIEF-ENCOUNTER-With-Tony-Taccone- |date=2011-02-10 }}.</ref> During his tenure, Berkeley Rep has emerged as the source of many important Broadway shows, including Green Day's ''American Idiot,'' Sarah Ruhl's ''In the Next Room, or the vibrator play,'' Carrie Fisher's ''Wishful Drinking,'' Sarah Jones' ''Bridge & Tunnel,'' and ''Passing Strange.'' <ref name=Hurwitt2>HURWITT, ROBERT (October 16, 2009), \"Berkeley Rep a big success on Broadway\". ''San Francisco Chronicle''.</ref><ref name=WEBER>WEBER, BRUCE (October 25, 2009), \"Two Tonys and Their 'Tiny' Five-Act Play\". ''New York Times''.</ref> Two of Taccone\u2019s recent shows also transferred to London: ''Continental Divide'' played the Barbican in 2004, and ''Tiny Kushner'' played the Tricycle Theatre in 2010.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/> \n\nTaccone's professional career has included fostering [[clowning]], a fascination he developed when he went to take his small family to see the [[Pickle Family Circus]] in the 1980s.  He favors clown artistry that is a reaction to tragedy.<ref name=McLaughlin/>\n\nTaccone has been called a \"theatrical midwife\" because he often encourages and fosters new talent.<ref name=McLaughlin/>  Examples include his work with Sarah Jones on ''Surface Transit'' and the aforementioned Tony Kushner.<ref name=McLaughlin/>\n\nIn 2009, Taccone participated in ''A Night With the Stars'', a play performed by persons who were previously homeless. The play was done as a fundraiser for [[Community Housing Partnership]] in San Francisco.<ref>Rubien, David (April 19, 2009), [http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/c/a/2009/04/19/PK9816MSAE.DTL&hw=tony+taccone&sn=003&sc=492 \"This week: Arts and entertainment picks\"]. SFGate.com (accessed 2009-05-19)</ref>\n\nTaccone made his playwriting debut in May 2011 with his solo show for Rita Moreno<ref>Jones, Kenneth (March 3, 2010) [http://www.playbill.com/news/article/137473-Lemony-Snicket-Rita-Moreno-The-Great-Game-Will-Be-Part-of-Berkeley-Rep-in-2010-11-Season-Announced \"Lemony Snicket, Rita Moreno, The Great Game Will Be Part of Berkeley Rep in 2010-11; Season Announced\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100306072221/http://www.playbill.com/news/article/137473-Lemony-Snicket-Rita-Moreno-The-Great-Game-Will-Be-Part-of-Berkeley-Rep-in-2010-11-Season-Announced |date=2010-03-06 }}</ref> and followed this up with his show ''Ghost Light'' at the Oregon Shakespeare Festival in 2011, which he co-created with Jonathan Moscone.<ref>Hughley, Marty (March 12, 2010), [http://www.oregonlive.com/performance/index.ssf/2010/03/oregon_shakespeare_festival_an_3.html \"Ashland's Oregon Shakespeare Festival announces plays for 2011 season\"].</ref>\n\nIn 2019, Taccone ended his 33 year tenure as Artistic Director of [[Berkeley Repertory Theatre]], handing the position over to Johanna Pfaelzer. \n\n==Personal life==\n{{quote box|width=280px|quote=You can have a healthy, happy life and still be indelibly connected to the deeper sorrow of the world. You don't need to create personal trauma to experience darkness. In fact, in some rarefied theological schools of thought, one could argue the opposite.<ref name=McLaughlin/>|source=''American Theater'' magazine, 2006}}\n\nTaccone is married to Morgan Forsey.<ref name=\"Bigelow\">{{cite news |last1=Bigelow |first1=Catherine |title=Cal Shakes gala raises curtain on education |url=https://www.pressreader.com/ |accessdate=3 February 2019 |work=San Francisco Chronicle |date=March 20, 2013}}</ref> Taccone's children include [[Jorma Taccone]],<ref>Jones, Chad (August 30, 2007), [http://blogs.mercurynews.com/aei/2007/08/30/brt40-a-chat-with-tony-taccone/ \"BRT@40: A chat with Tony Taccone\"]{{Dead link|date=July 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=no }}. MercuryNews.com (accessed 2009-05-18)</ref> (a member of the sketch-comedy troupe [[the Lonely Island]] and a former-writer for ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'') and [[Asa Taccone]], a musician and sometimes collaborator with his brother.<ref name=Hurwitt/>  Asa is a founding member of the band [[Electric Guest]] and has composed music for his father's productions, such as for ''Bridge & Tunnel'' and Taking Over.<ref>SCHIFFMAN, JEAN (January 22, 2006), [http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117936534.html?categoryId=1228&cs=1 \"Helmer Taccone expands his 'Tunnel' vision\"]. Variety.com (accessed 2009-05-19)</ref><ref>BWW News Desk (January 21, 2009), [http://broadwayworld.com/people/news/Danny_Hoch/ \"Danny Hoch's TAKING OVER Previews Tonight 1/21\"]. BroadwayWorld.com (accessed 2009-05-19)</ref>\n\n==Theater credits==\n*''Honour'', Berkeley Repertory Theatre - director\n*''Continental Divide'', Berkeley Repertory Theatre - director\n*''Surface Transit'', Berkeley Repertory Theatre - director\n*''Cloud Nine'', Berkeley Repertory Theatre - director\n*''Homebody/Kabul'', Berkeley Repertory Theatre - director\n*''Culture Clash in AmeriCCa'', Berkeley Repertory Theatre - director\n*''The Oresteia'', Berkeley Repertory Theatre - director\n*''Ravenshead'', Berkeley Repertory Theatre - director\n*''Pentecost, Slavs!'', Berkeley Repertory Theatre - director\n*''The Caucasian Chalk Circle'', Berkeley Repertory Theatre - director\n*''Endgame/Act Without Words'', Berkeley Repertory Theatre - director\n*''Volpone'', Berkeley Repertory Theatre - director\n*''The Convict\u2019s Return'', Berkeley Repertory Theatre - director\n*''Major Barbara'', Berkeley Repertory Theatre - director\n*''Serious Money'', Berkeley Repertory Theatre - director\n*''Waiting for Godot'' - director\n*''[[Othello]]'', Oregon Shakespeare Festival - director\n*Pentecost, Oregon Shakespeare Festival - director\n*''[[Coriolanus]]'', Oregon Shakespeare Festival - director\n*''[[The Cure at Troy]]'', Oregon Shakespeare Festival - director\n*''The Birthday Party and Execution of Justice'', Berkeley Repertory Theatre\n* ''[[Waiting for Godot]]'' (1989) - director\n* ''[[Angels in America]], Parts One and Two'', Mark Taper Forum (1992) - director\n* ''Brundibar'' (2006), New Victory Theater - director\n* ''Zorro in Hell'' (2006) - director\n* ''Wishful Drinking'' (2008), Berkeley Repertory Theatre - director<ref>Hurwitt, Robert (April 30, 2009), [http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/c/a/2009/04/30/DDTP17ATQ4.DTL&hw=tony+taccone&sn=001&sc=1000 \"Fisher's 'Wishful Drinking' is Broadway-bound\"]. (SFGate.com. (accessed 2009-05-19)</ref>\n* ''Taking Over'', (2009) - director\n*Kiss My Aztec, (2019), Berkeley Repertory Theatre - director\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/blogs/chroncast/detail?blogid=5&entry_id=6727 Tony Taccone, Berkeley Rep Theatre's artistic director], podcast <small>([http://cdn.sfgate.com/blogs/sounds/sfgate/chroncast/2006/07/03/BackStory-Taccone-20060705.mp3 audio link])</small>\n\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Taccone, Tony}}\n[[Category:1951 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American theatre directors]]\n[[Category:American people of Italian descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Puerto Rican descent]]\n[[Category:Boston College alumni]]\n[[Category:Theatre in the San Francisco Bay Area]]\n[[Category:People from the San Francisco Bay Area]]\n", "name_user": "Seub", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added \"Kiss my Aztec\" musical", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tony_Taccone"}
{"title_page": "Robert Leadley", "text_new": "{{Infobox baseball biography\n|name=Bob Leadley\n|position=[[Manager (baseball)|Manager]], owner\n|image=R. H. Leadley.png\n|bats=Right\n|throws=Unknown\n|birth_date={{Birth date|1858|11|11|mf=y}}\n|birth_place=[[Brooklyn, New York]]\n|death_date={{death date and age|1936|5|19|1858|11|11}}\n|death_place=[[Los Angeles, California]]\n|debutleague = MLB\n|debutdate=\n|debutyear=\n|debutteam=\n|finalleague = MLB\n|finaldate=\n|finalyear=\n|finalteam=\n|statleague = MLB\n|stat1label=\n|stat1value=\n|stat2label=\n|stat2value=\n|stat3label=\n|stat3value=\n|stat4label=Managerial record\n|stat4value=76-86 \n|teams=\n'''As manager'''\n*[[Detroit Wolverines]] (1888)\n*[[Cleveland Spiders]] (1890\u201391)\n'''As owner'''\n*[[Seattle Yannigans/Rainmakers]] (1896)\n*[[Grand Rapids Bob-o-links]] (1897)\n}}\n'''Robert H. \"Bob\" Leadley''' (November 11, 1858 &ndash; May 19, 1936) was a professional [[baseball]] manager, administrator, and team owner whose career spanned from 1884 to 1897.  He was a manager in [[Major League Baseball]] for the last portion of the 1888 season with the [[Detroit Wolverines]] and for parts of the 1890 and 1891 seasons with the [[Cleveland Spiders]]. Over those three seasons, Leadley compiled a record of 76-86 and a winning percentage of .469.\n\nLeadley was also one of the organizers of the [[New Pacific League]], one of the first baseball leagues on the west coast, and co-owner with [[Bob Glenalvin]] of the short-lived [[Seattle Yannigans/Rainmakers]] in 1896 and the [[Grand Rapids Bob-o-links]] in 1897.\n\nIn 1899, Leadley was removed from his position as clerk of the Police Court in Detroit after $10,000 was discovered missing. A warrant was issued for Leadley's arrest, but he fled to [[Mexico City]] as a fugitive where he lived for at least the next ten years.\n\n==Early years==\nLeadley was born in [[Brooklyn, New York]], in 1858.<ref name=BR /> He moved to [[Detroit]] where he worked as an accountant and also managed the Cass Club baseball team in the early 1880s.<ref name=Bio>{{cite news|title=Sketch of Manager Leadley of the Grand Rapids Club of the Western League|newspaper=Kansas Agitator|date=October 1, 1897|page=7}}</ref>  In December 1881, he was married to  Mattie Jane Long in Detroit.<ref name=NMP>{{cite web|title=Baseball Biographical Research - Notes on Missing Players|url=http://hoxley.tripod.com/L.index.html}}</ref>\n\n==Professional baseball==\n\n===Detroit Wolverines===\nLeadley served as the Secretary of the [[Detroit Wolverines]] baseball club from 1884 to 1888 with principal responsibility for handling the club's finances. He was also the head of the Cass Club baseball club in Detroit.<ref name=DFP88/>\n\nIn late August 1888, the [[Detroit Wolverines]] fired, or accepted the resignation of, [[Bill Watkins]] as their manager; Leadley was hired as \"acting manager\" in his place.  When asked what he was going to do about the team's downward spiral, he replied, \"I hardly know.  The outlook is not very brilliant, but I shall take hold and do the best I can and trust the rest to fortune.\"<ref name=DFP88>{{cite web|title=Watkins Steps Down: His Resignation Accepted by the Directors of the Club And Robert H. Leadley Appointed Acting Manager|newspaper=Detroit Free Press |date=August 28, 1888 |page=8 |url=https://secure.pqarchiver.com/freep/doc/561928651.html?FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:AI&type=historic&date=Aug+28%2C+1888&author=&pub=Detroit+Free+Press+%281858-1922%29&edition=&startpage=&desc=WATKINS+STEPS+DOWN.}}</ref>  Leadley managed the team for the last 38 games of the season and compiled a 19-19 record.<ref name=\"BR\">{{cite web|title=Bob Leadley Managerial Record|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|work=baseball-reference.com|accessdate=June 9, 2014|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/managers/leadlbo99.shtml}}</ref>\n\nAt the end of the 1888 season, the Detroit Wolverines left the National League, and most of the players were sold to other clubs.  A new Detroit Wolverines team was formed for the 1889 as part of the International League. Leadley served as the Wolverines' manager in 1889 and 1890.<ref name=\"BR Minor\">{{cite web|title=Bob Leadley Minor League Record|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|work=baseball-reference.com|accessdate=June 9, 2014|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/minors/player.cgi?id=leadle001rob}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Manager Leadley At Home: He Talks About the Trip, the Team and the Outlook|newspaper=Detroit Free Press|date=April 26, 1889 |page=8 |url=https://secure.pqarchiver.com/freep/doc/561988010.html?FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:AI&type=historic&date=Apr+26%2C+1889&author=&pub=Detroit+Free+Press+%281858-1922%29&edition=&startpage=&desc=MANAGER+LEADLEY+AT+HOME.}}</ref>  The 1889 Detroit club compiled a 72-39 record,<ref name=Bio/> and was, according to its star outfielder [[Count Campau]], \"one of the greatest minor league teams gathered\" and \"won the flag so easy that fans stopped going out to see the games.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Count Campau's Plans: Detroit Man Will Be With Rochester This Season; Interesting Review of His Career on the Diamond|newspaper=Detroit Free Press|date=March 13, 1899|page=8}}</ref>  He continued to manage the Detroit team until it disbanded part way through the 1890 season.<ref name=Bio/>\n\n===Cleveland Spiders===\nAfter the Detroit team disbanded, Leadley was hired as the manager of the [[Cleveland Spiders]].  With pitcher [[Cy Young]] learning the ropes in his first major league season, the Spiders compiles a 23-33 record under Leadley and finished in seventh place in the National League.<ref name=BR />\n\nLeadley returned as the Spiders' manager in 1891 and compiled a 34-34 record through the first 68 games.<ref name=BR /> On July 11, 1891, Leadley resigned as manager of the Spiders, and his resignation was accepted.  He was replaced as manager by the team's third baseman, [[Patsy Tebeau]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Leadley Resigns|newspaper=Pittsburg Dispatch|date=July 12, 1891|page=6}}</ref>\n\n===Minor leagues and civil service===\nIn August 1891, shortly after being removed as Cleveland's manager, Leadley was hired as manager of the [[Omaha, Nebraska]] club in the Western Association. At the time, the ''Omaha Daily Bee'' wrote: \"In Manager Leadley Omaha has a manager she can feel proud of. He is an educated, cultured gentleman, and ranks high in the estimation of the base ball world.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Base Ball: Good Words for Bob Leadley|newspaper=Detroit Free Press (reprinted from Omaha Daily Bee)|date=August 31, 1891|page=6|url=https://secure.pqarchiver.com/freep/doc/562225441.html?FMT=CITE&FMTS=CITE:AI&type=historic&date=Aug+31%2C+1891&author=&pub=Detroit+Free+Press+%281858-1922%29&edition=&startpage=&desc=BASE+BALL.}}</ref>\n\nIn April 1892, Leadley was hired as manager of the Buffalo team in the Eastern League. ''The Sun'' newspaper from New York wrote at the time: \"In Bob Leadley Buffalo has secured a shrewd and able manager.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Baseball Notes|newspaper=The Sun (New York)|date=April 1, 1892|page=4}}</ref> However, a short time after the announcement, Leadley stated that he would not move to Buffalo and would keep his position in Detroit with the United States internal revenue office.<ref>{{cite news|title=Yelps from the Bleachers|newspaper=The Omaha Daily Bee|date=April 17, 1892|page=13}}</ref>\n\nLeadley remained in the civil service in 1893 and 1894.  He served as the assistant cashier at the revenue office during those years.<ref name=Bio/>  In July 1894, he was appointed as the chief clerk of the Police Court in Detroit.<ref>{{cite news|title=\"Bob\" Leadley Gets It: He Will be Chief Clerk of the Police Court for the Next Two Years|newspaper=Detroit Free Press |date=July 25, 1894 |page=8 |url=https://secure.pqarchiver.com/freep/doc/562500991.html?FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:AI&type=historic&date=Jul+25%2C+1894&author=&pub=Detroit+Free+Press+%281858-1922%29&edition=&startpage=&desc=%22BOB%22+LEADLEY+GETS+IT.}}</ref>\n\n===Team owner in Seattle and Grand Rapids===\nIn 1896, Leadley formed a partnership with [[Bob Glenalvin]], manager of the [[Detroit Tigers]] in 1894, and others to re-establish the [[Pacific Northwest League]] as the [[New Pacific League]].  Leadley became the owner of the [[Seattle Yannigans/Rainmakers]] franchise and hired [[Count Campau]], who he had managed in Detroit, as Seattle's player/manager.  However, the league folded by the middle of June 1896.<ref name=Bio/><ref name=NCS>{{cite book|title=Nineteenth Century Stars: 2012 Edition|author=Cappy Gagnon|pages=48\u201349}}</ref>  After the collapse of the New Pacific League, Leadley returned to Detroit.<ref name=Bio/>\n\nIn November 1896, Leadley and Glenalvin purchased the Western Association baseball franchise in [[Grand Rapids, Michigan]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Ellis Has Sold Out: Grand Rapids Passed to Leadley and Glenalvin; The Deal Was Secretly Consummated on Monday; New Owners Promise Plenty of Good Ball Playing |newspaper=Detroit Free Press|date=November 18, 1896 |page=6 |url=https://secure.pqarchiver.com/freep/doc/562767064.html?FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:AI&type=historic&date=Nov+18%2C+1896&author=&pub=Detroit+Free+Press+%281858-1922%29&edition=&startpage=&desc=ELLIS+HAS+SOLD+OUT}}</ref>  The two owned the team, known as the [[Grand Rapids Bob-o-links]], during the 1897 season and hired Count Campau as player-manager with Glenalvin playing at second base.  Late in the 1897 season, Leadley bought Glenalvin's interest and became sole owner of the club.<ref name=Bio/>\n\n==Embezzlement and fugitive==\nIn the late 1890s, even as he was the owner of the Grand Rapids baseball club, Leadley continued to serve as the clerk of Detroit's Police Court.<ref>{{cite news|title=Police Court Books: Being Examined at Clerk Leadley's Suggestion|newspaper=Detroit Free Press |date=August 22, 1897 |page=10|url=https://secure.pqarchiver.com/freep/doc/562782821.html?FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:AI&type=historic&date=Aug+22%2C+1897&author=&pub=Detroit+Free+Press+%281858-1922%29&edition=&startpage=&desc=POLICE+COURT+BOOKS.}}</ref>  In August 1897, an audit revealed he owed the county the sum of $4,208, admitted he had been neglectful, and promptly paid the sum owed.<ref>{{cite news|title=Back In His Payments: Robert H. Leadley Owes the County the Sum of $4,209; He Admits He Was Neglectful, But Will Pay; Former Clerks, He Asserts, Have Been Very Slos|newspaper=Detroit Free Press|date=August 24, 1897 |page=5 |url=https://secure.pqarchiver.com/freep/doc/562777238.html?FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:AI&type=historic&date=Aug+24%2C+1897&author=&pub=Detroit+Free+Press+%281858-1922%29&edition=&startpage=&desc=BACK+IN+HIS+PAYMENTS}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Leadley Paid Up|newspaper=Detroit Free Press|date=August 25, 1897 |page=10 |url=https://secure.pqarchiver.com/freep/doc/562863591.html?FMT=CITE&FMTS=CITE:AI&type=historic&date=Aug+25%2C+1897&author=&pub=Detroit+Free+Press+%281858-1922%29&edition=&startpage=&desc=LEADLEY+PAID+UP.}}</ref> He continued in his position as clerk despite a call by the ''Detroit Free Press'' in September 1897 for his discharge.<ref>{{cite news|title=He Should Be Discharged|newspaper=Detroit Free Press |date=September 8, 1897 |page=4|url=https://secure.pqarchiver.com/freep/doc/562779092.html?FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:AI&type=historic&date=Sep+8%2C+1897&author=&pub=Detroit+Free+Press+%281858-1922%29&edition=&startpage=&desc=HE+SHOULD+BE+DISCHARGED.}}</ref>\n\nIn January 1899, Leadley was removed as the Police Court clerk after an investigation revealed a new shortage of approximately $10,000 in his books.  When the shortage was discovered, Leadley was reported to be missing, and a warrant was issued for his arrest.<ref>{{cite news|title=He's Gone!  Robert H. Leadley Far Outside Detroit; With Plenty of Money He Is In a Summery Clime|newspaper=Detroit Free Press|date=January 31, 1899|page=2|url=https://secure.pqarchiver.com/freep/doc/562982343.html?FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:AI&type=historic&date=Jan+31%2C+1899&author=&pub=Detroit+Free+Press+%281858-1922%29&edition=&startpage=&desc=HE%27S+GONE%21}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Will Mount Up To $10,000: Leadley's Shortage Will Prove No Bagatelle; Council Took Cognizance of Situation; Prosecuting Attorney to be Handed the Evidence|newspaper=Detroit Free Press |date=February 1, 1899 |page=10 |url=https://secure.pqarchiver.com/freep/doc/562959259.html?FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:AI&type=historic&date=Feb+1%2C+1899&author=&pub=Detroit+Free+Press+%281858-1922%29&edition=&startpage=&desc=WILL+MOUNT+UP+TO+%2410%2C000}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Warrant for Leadley|newspaper=Detroit Free Press |date=February 4, 1899 |page=10|url=https://secure.pqarchiver.com/freep/doc/563022484.html?FMT=CITE&FMTS=CITE:AI&type=historic&date=Feb+4%2C+1899&author=&pub=Detroit+Free+Press+%281858-1922%29&edition=&startpage=&desc=Warrant+for+Leadley.}}</ref>  By March 1899, Leadley was still in hiding as the city accountant reported that, even as the investigation was nearing its end, additional funds had been embezzled during Leadley's final days in office.<ref>{{cite news|title=Leadley's Duplcity: He Kept It Up Even After Discovered|newspaper=Detroit Free Press |date=March 5, 1899 |page=A3 |url=https://secure.pqarchiver.com/freep/doc/563021908.html?FMT=AI&FMTS=AI:CITE&type=historic&date=Mar+5%2C+1899&author=&pub=Detroit+Free+Press+%281858-1922%29&desc=LEADLEY%27S+DUPLICITY.}}</ref>\n\nIn 1900, Leadley remained on the run and was reported to be living with his wife in Mexico City.<ref name=NMP/><ref>{{cite news|title=Saw Bob Leadley: Gabriel Chiera Met Him in Mexico City|newspaper=Detroit Free Press |date=April 8, 1900 |page=10|url=https://secure.pqarchiver.com/freep/doc/563144639.html?FMT=CITE&FMTS=CITE:AI&type=historic&date=Apr+8%2C+1900&author=&pub=Detroit+Free+Press+%281858-1922%29&edition=&startpage=&desc=SAW+BOB+LEADLY.}}</ref>  In 1907, a report was published that Leadley was tired of living in Mexico City, and his friends offered to pay the city $2,000 in exchange for a grant of immunity.<ref>{{cite news|title=Leadley Said to Be Tired of Mexico|newspaper=Detroit Free Press |date=January 19, 1907 |page=8 |url=https://secure.pqarchiver.com/freep/doc/563985910.html?FMT=CITE&FMTS=CITE:AI&type=historic&date=Jan+19%2C+1907&author=&pub=Detroit+Free+Press+%281858-1922%29&edition=&startpage=&desc=Leadley+Said+to+Be+Tired+of+Mexico.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Can't Give Leadley Immunity|newspaper=Detroit Free Press|date=January 30, 1907|page=5|url=https://secure.pqarchiver.com/freep/doc/563839508.html?FMT=CITE&FMTS=CITE:AI&type=historic&date=Jan+30%2C+1907&author=&pub=Detroit+Free+Press+%281858-1922%29&edition=&startpage=&desc=Can%27t+Give+Leadley+Immunity.}}</ref>  No deal was struck, and friends of Leadley, including [[Frank Bowerman]], continued in their efforts to negotiate a deal on his behalf into 1909.<ref>{{cite news|title=In Aid of Leadley: Walsh and Bowerman Hope to Get Exile Home Again|newspaper=Detroit Free Press|date=February 19, 1909|page=10|url=https://secure.pqarchiver.com/freep/doc/564287210.html?FMT=CITE&FMTS=CITE:AI&type=historic&date=Feb+19%2C+1909&author=&pub=Detroit+Free+Press+%281858-1922%29&edition=&startpage=&desc=IN+AID+OF+LEADLEY}}</ref>  In 1910, he was reported to be living in [[Torre\u00f3n|Torion]], Mexico.<ref name=NMP/>\n\n==Later years==\nLeadley died in [[Los Angeles]] in 1936.<ref name=BR /> According to California death records, he had been living in Los Angeles since 1922 with his wife who was identified as \"Matha\" Leadley.<ref name=NMP />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Leadley, Robert}}\n[[Category:1858 births]]\n[[Category:1936 deaths]]\n[[Category:Baseball managers]]\n[[Category:Detroit Wolverines managers]]\n[[Category:Cleveland Spiders managers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox baseball biography\n|name=Bob Leadley\n|position=[[Manager (baseball)|Manager]], owner\n|image=R. H. Leadley.png\n|bats=Right\n|throws=Unknown\n|birth_date={{Birth date|1858|11|11|mf=y}}\n|birth_place=[[Brooklyn, New York]]\n|death_date={{death date and age|1936|5|19|1858|11|11}}\n|death_place=[[Los Angeles, California]]\n|debutleague = MLB\n|debutdate=\n|debutyear=\n|debutteam=\n|finalleague = MLB\n|finaldate=\n|finalyear=\n|finalteam=\n|statleague = MLB\n|stat1label=\n|stat1value=\n|stat2label=\n|stat2value=\n|stat3label=\n|stat3value=\n|stat4label=Managerial record\n|stat4value=76-86 \n|teams=\n'''As manager'''\n*[[Detroit Wolverines]] (1888)\n*[[Cleveland Spiders]] (1890\u201391)\n'''As owner'''\n*[[Seattle Yannigans/Rainmakers]] (1896)\n*[[Grand Rapids Bob-o-links]] (1897)\n}}\n'''Robert H. \"Bob\" Leadley''' (November 11, 1858 &ndash; May 19, 1936) was a professional [[baseball]] manager, administrator, and team owner whose career spanned from 1884 to 1897.  He was a manager in [[Major League Baseball]] for the last portion of the 1888 season with the [[Detroit Wolverines]] and for parts of the 1890 and 1891 seasons with the [[Cleveland Spiders]]. Over those three seasons, Leadley compiled a record of 76-86 and a winning percentage of .469.\n\nLeadley was also one of the organizers of the [[New Pacific League]], one of the first baseball leagues on the west coast, and co-owner with [[Bob Glenalvin]] of the short-lived [[Seattle Yannigans/Rainmakers]] in 1896 and the [[Grand Rapids Bob-o-links]] in 1897.\n\nIn 1899, Leadley was removed from his position as clerk of the Police Court in Detroit after $10,000 was discovered missing. A warrant was issued for Leadley's arrest, but he fled to [[Mexico City]] as a fugitive where he lived for at least the next ten years.\n\n==Early years==\nLeadley was born in [[Brooklyn, New York]], in 1858.<ref name=BR/>  He moved to [[Detroit]] where he worked as an accountant and also managed the Cass Club baseball team in the early 1880s.<ref name=Bio>{{cite news|title=Sketch of Manager Leadley of the Grand Rapids Club of the Western League|newspaper=Kansas Agitator|date=October 1, 1897|page=7}}</ref>  In December 1881, he was married to  Mattie Jane Long in Detroit.<ref name=NMP>{{cite web|title=Baseball Biographical Research - Notes on Missing Players|url=http://hoxley.tripod.com/L.index.html}}</ref>\n\n==Professional baseball==\n\n===Detroit Wolverines===\nLeadley served as the Secretary of the [[Detroit Wolverines]] baseball club from 1884 to 1888 with principal responsibility for handling the club's finances. He was also the head of the Cass Club baseball club in Detroit.<ref name=DFP88/>\n\nIn late August 1888, the [[Detroit Wolverines]] fired, or accepted the resignation of, [[Bill Watkins]] as their manager; Leadley was hired as \"acting manager\" in his place.  When asked what he was going to do about the team's downward spiral, he replied, \"I hardly know.  The outlook is not very brilliant, but I shall take hold and do the best I can and trust the rest to fortune.\"<ref name=DFP88>{{cite web|title=Watkins Steps Down: His Resignation Accepted by the Directors of the Club And Robert H. Leadley Appointed Acting Manager|newspaper=Detroit Free Press |date=August 28, 1888 |page=8 |url=https://secure.pqarchiver.com/freep/doc/561928651.html?FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:AI&type=historic&date=Aug+28%2C+1888&author=&pub=Detroit+Free+Press+%281858-1922%29&edition=&startpage=&desc=WATKINS+STEPS+DOWN.}}</ref>  Leadley managed the team for the last 38 games of the season and compiled a 19-19 record.<ref name=BR>{{cite web|title=Bob Leadley Managerial Record|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|work=baseball-reference.com|accessdate=June 9, 2014|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/managers/leadlbo99.shtml}}</ref>\n\nAt the end of the 1888 season, the Detroit Wolverines left the National League, and most of the players were sold to other clubs.  A new Detroit Wolverines team was formed for the 1889 as part of the International League. Leadley served as the Wolverines' manager in 1889 and 1890.<ref name=BR>{{cite web|title=Bob Leadley Minor League Record|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|work=baseball-reference.com|accessdate=June 9, 2014|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/minors/player.cgi?id=leadle001rob}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Manager Leadley At Home: He Talks About the Trip, the Team and the Outlook|newspaper=Detroit Free Press|date=April 26, 1889 |page=8 |url=https://secure.pqarchiver.com/freep/doc/561988010.html?FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:AI&type=historic&date=Apr+26%2C+1889&author=&pub=Detroit+Free+Press+%281858-1922%29&edition=&startpage=&desc=MANAGER+LEADLEY+AT+HOME.}}</ref>  The 1889 Detroit club compiled a 72-39 record,<ref name=Bio/> and was, according to its star outfielder [[Count Campau]], \"one of the greatest minor league teams gathered\" and \"won the flag so easy that fans stopped going out to see the games.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Count Campau's Plans: Detroit Man Will Be With Rochester This Season; Interesting Review of His Career on the Diamond|newspaper=Detroit Free Press|date=March 13, 1899|page=8}}</ref>  He continued to manage the Detroit team until it disbanded part way through the 1890 season.<ref name=Bio/>\n\n===Cleveland Spiders===\nAfter the Detroit team disbanded, Leadley was hired as the manager of the [[Cleveland Spiders]].  With pitcher [[Cy Young]] learning the ropes in his first major league season, the Spiders compiles a 23-33 record under Leadley and finished in seventh place in the National League.<ref name=BR/>\n\nLeadley returned as the Spiders' manager in 1891 and compiled a 34-34 record through the first 68 games.<ref name=BR/>  On July 11, 1891, Leadley resigned as manager of the Spiders, and his resignation was accepted.  He was replaced as manager by the team's third baseman, [[Patsy Tebeau]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Leadley Resigns|newspaper=Pittsburg Dispatch|date=July 12, 1891|page=6}}</ref>\n\n===Minor leagues and civil service===\nIn August 1891, shortly after being removed as Cleveland's manager, Leadley was hired as manager of the [[Omaha, Nebraska]] club in the Western Association. At the time, the ''Omaha Daily Bee'' wrote: \"In Manager Leadley Omaha has a manager she can feel proud of. He is an educated, cultured gentleman, and ranks high in the estimation of the base ball world.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Base Ball: Good Words for Bob Leadley|newspaper=Detroit Free Press (reprinted from Omaha Daily Bee)|date=August 31, 1891|page=6|url=https://secure.pqarchiver.com/freep/doc/562225441.html?FMT=CITE&FMTS=CITE:AI&type=historic&date=Aug+31%2C+1891&author=&pub=Detroit+Free+Press+%281858-1922%29&edition=&startpage=&desc=BASE+BALL.}}</ref>\n\nIn April 1892, Leadley was hired as manager of the Buffalo team in the Eastern League. ''The Sun'' newspaper from New York wrote at the time: \"In Bob Leadley Buffalo has secured a shrewd and able manager.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Baseball Notes|newspaper=The Sun (New York)|date=April 1, 1892|page=4}}</ref> However, a short time after the announcement, Leadley stated that he would not move to Buffalo and would keep his position in Detroit with the United States internal revenue office.<ref>{{cite news|title=Yelps from the Bleachers|newspaper=The Omaha Daily Bee|date=April 17, 1892|page=13}}</ref>\n\nLeadley remained in the civil service in 1893 and 1894.  He served as the assistant cashier at the revenue office during those years.<ref name=Bio/>  In July 1894, he was appointed as the chief clerk of the Police Court in Detroit.<ref>{{cite news|title=\"Bob\" Leadley Gets It: He Will be Chief Clerk of the Police Court for the Next Two Years|newspaper=Detroit Free Press |date=July 25, 1894 |page=8 |url=https://secure.pqarchiver.com/freep/doc/562500991.html?FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:AI&type=historic&date=Jul+25%2C+1894&author=&pub=Detroit+Free+Press+%281858-1922%29&edition=&startpage=&desc=%22BOB%22+LEADLEY+GETS+IT.}}</ref>\n\n===Team owner in Seattle and Grand Rapids===\nIn 1896, Leadley formed a partnership with [[Bob Glenalvin]], manager of the [[Detroit Tigers]] in 1894, and others to re-establish the [[Pacific Northwest League]] as the [[New Pacific League]].  Leadley became the owner of the [[Seattle Yannigans/Rainmakers]] franchise and hired [[Count Campau]], who he had managed in Detroit, as Seattle's player/manager.  However, the league folded by the middle of June 1896.<ref name=Bio/><ref name=NCS>{{cite book|title=Nineteenth Century Stars: 2012 Edition|author=Cappy Gagnon|pages=48\u201349}}</ref>  After the collapse of the New Pacific League, Leadley returned to Detroit.<ref name=Bio/>\n\nIn November 1896, Leadley and Glenalvin purchased the Western Association baseball franchise in [[Grand Rapids, Michigan]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Ellis Has Sold Out: Grand Rapids Passed to Leadley and Glenalvin; The Deal Was Secretly Consummated on Monday; New Owners Promise Plenty of Good Ball Playing |newspaper=Detroit Free Press|date=November 18, 1896 |page=6 |url=https://secure.pqarchiver.com/freep/doc/562767064.html?FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:AI&type=historic&date=Nov+18%2C+1896&author=&pub=Detroit+Free+Press+%281858-1922%29&edition=&startpage=&desc=ELLIS+HAS+SOLD+OUT}}</ref>  The two owned the team, known as the [[Grand Rapids Bob-o-links]], during the 1897 season and hired Count Campau as player-manager with Glenalvin playing at second base.  Late in the 1897 season, Leadley bought Glenalvin's interest and became sole owner of the club.<ref name=Bio/>\n\n==Embezzlement and fugitive==\nIn the late 1890s, even as he was the owner of the Grand Rapids baseball club, Leadley continued to serve as the clerk of Detroit's Police Court.<ref>{{cite news|title=Police Court Books: Being Examined at Clerk Leadley's Suggestion|newspaper=Detroit Free Press |date=August 22, 1897 |page=10|url=https://secure.pqarchiver.com/freep/doc/562782821.html?FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:AI&type=historic&date=Aug+22%2C+1897&author=&pub=Detroit+Free+Press+%281858-1922%29&edition=&startpage=&desc=POLICE+COURT+BOOKS.}}</ref>  In August 1897, an audit revealed he owed the county the sum of $4,208, admitted he had been neglectful, and promptly paid the sum owed.<ref>{{cite news|title=Back In His Payments: Robert H. Leadley Owes the County the Sum of $4,209; He Admits He Was Neglectful, But Will Pay; Former Clerks, He Asserts, Have Been Very Slos|newspaper=Detroit Free Press|date=August 24, 1897 |page=5 |url=https://secure.pqarchiver.com/freep/doc/562777238.html?FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:AI&type=historic&date=Aug+24%2C+1897&author=&pub=Detroit+Free+Press+%281858-1922%29&edition=&startpage=&desc=BACK+IN+HIS+PAYMENTS}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Leadley Paid Up|newspaper=Detroit Free Press|date=August 25, 1897 |page=10 |url=https://secure.pqarchiver.com/freep/doc/562863591.html?FMT=CITE&FMTS=CITE:AI&type=historic&date=Aug+25%2C+1897&author=&pub=Detroit+Free+Press+%281858-1922%29&edition=&startpage=&desc=LEADLEY+PAID+UP.}}</ref> He continued in his position as clerk despite a call by the ''Detroit Free Press'' in September 1897 for his discharge.<ref>{{cite news|title=He Should Be Discharged|newspaper=Detroit Free Press |date=September 8, 1897 |page=4|url=https://secure.pqarchiver.com/freep/doc/562779092.html?FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:AI&type=historic&date=Sep+8%2C+1897&author=&pub=Detroit+Free+Press+%281858-1922%29&edition=&startpage=&desc=HE+SHOULD+BE+DISCHARGED.}}</ref>\n\nIn January 1899, Leadley was removed as the Police Court clerk after an investigation revealed a new shortage of approximately $10,000 in his books.  When the shortage was discovered, Leadley was reported to be missing, and a warrant was issued for his arrest.<ref>{{cite news|title=He's Gone!  Robert H. Leadley Far Outside Detroit; With Plenty of Money He Is In a Summery Clime|newspaper=Detroit Free Press|date=January 31, 1899|page=2|url=https://secure.pqarchiver.com/freep/doc/562982343.html?FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:AI&type=historic&date=Jan+31%2C+1899&author=&pub=Detroit+Free+Press+%281858-1922%29&edition=&startpage=&desc=HE%27S+GONE%21}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Will Mount Up To $10,000: Leadley's Shortage Will Prove No Bagatelle; Council Took Cognizance of Situation; Prosecuting Attorney to be Handed the Evidence|newspaper=Detroit Free Press |date=February 1, 1899 |page=10 |url=https://secure.pqarchiver.com/freep/doc/562959259.html?FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:AI&type=historic&date=Feb+1%2C+1899&author=&pub=Detroit+Free+Press+%281858-1922%29&edition=&startpage=&desc=WILL+MOUNT+UP+TO+%2410%2C000}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Warrant for Leadley|newspaper=Detroit Free Press |date=February 4, 1899 |page=10|url=https://secure.pqarchiver.com/freep/doc/563022484.html?FMT=CITE&FMTS=CITE:AI&type=historic&date=Feb+4%2C+1899&author=&pub=Detroit+Free+Press+%281858-1922%29&edition=&startpage=&desc=Warrant+for+Leadley.}}</ref>  By March 1899, Leadley was still in hiding as the city accountant reported that, even as the investigation was nearing its end, additional funds had been embezzled during Leadley's final days in office.<ref>{{cite news|title=Leadley's Duplcity: He Kept It Up Even After Discovered|newspaper=Detroit Free Press |date=March 5, 1899 |page=A3 |url=https://secure.pqarchiver.com/freep/doc/563021908.html?FMT=AI&FMTS=AI:CITE&type=historic&date=Mar+5%2C+1899&author=&pub=Detroit+Free+Press+%281858-1922%29&desc=LEADLEY%27S+DUPLICITY.}}</ref>\n\nIn 1900, Leadley remained on the run and was reported to be living with his wife in Mexico City.<ref name=NMP/><ref>{{cite news|title=Saw Bob Leadley: Gabriel Chiera Met Him in Mexico City|newspaper=Detroit Free Press |date=April 8, 1900 |page=10|url=https://secure.pqarchiver.com/freep/doc/563144639.html?FMT=CITE&FMTS=CITE:AI&type=historic&date=Apr+8%2C+1900&author=&pub=Detroit+Free+Press+%281858-1922%29&edition=&startpage=&desc=SAW+BOB+LEADLY.}}</ref>  In 1907, a report was published that Leadley was tired of living in Mexico City, and his friends offered to pay the city $2,000 in exchange for a grant of immunity.<ref>{{cite news|title=Leadley Said to Be Tired of Mexico|newspaper=Detroit Free Press |date=January 19, 1907 |page=8 |url=https://secure.pqarchiver.com/freep/doc/563985910.html?FMT=CITE&FMTS=CITE:AI&type=historic&date=Jan+19%2C+1907&author=&pub=Detroit+Free+Press+%281858-1922%29&edition=&startpage=&desc=Leadley+Said+to+Be+Tired+of+Mexico.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Can't Give Leadley Immunity|newspaper=Detroit Free Press|date=January 30, 1907|page=5|url=https://secure.pqarchiver.com/freep/doc/563839508.html?FMT=CITE&FMTS=CITE:AI&type=historic&date=Jan+30%2C+1907&author=&pub=Detroit+Free+Press+%281858-1922%29&edition=&startpage=&desc=Can%27t+Give+Leadley+Immunity.}}</ref>  No deal was struck, and friends of Leadley, including [[Frank Bowerman]], continued in their efforts to negotiate a deal on his behalf into 1909.<ref>{{cite news|title=In Aid of Leadley: Walsh and Bowerman Hope to Get Exile Home Again|newspaper=Detroit Free Press|date=February 19, 1909|page=10|url=https://secure.pqarchiver.com/freep/doc/564287210.html?FMT=CITE&FMTS=CITE:AI&type=historic&date=Feb+19%2C+1909&author=&pub=Detroit+Free+Press+%281858-1922%29&edition=&startpage=&desc=IN+AID+OF+LEADLEY}}</ref>  In 1910, he was reported to be living in [[Torre\u00f3n|Torion]], Mexico.<ref name=NMP/>\n\n==Later years==\nLeadley died in [[Los Angeles]] in 1936.<ref name=BR/> According to California death records, he had been living in Los Angeles since 1922 with his wife who was identified as \"Matha\" Leadley.<ref name=NMP/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Leadley, Robert}}\n[[Category:1858 births]]\n[[Category:1936 deaths]]\n[[Category:Baseball managers]]\n[[Category:Detroit Wolverines managers]]\n[[Category:Cleveland Spiders managers]]\n", "name_user": "Quebec99", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fix duplicate ref names \u2013You can help!", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Robert_Leadley"}
